rmk: The clip records a flush of House Sparrows brought about by a false alarm. This, of course, is a regular occurrence among all birds that face the risk of predation constantly. The false alarm was caused by the sudden appearance of a group of wild Rock Doves that flew over a feeding area used by House Sparrows and Starlings. Not all the House Sparrows fled. Some dived into bushes. Soon all were back out in the open and feeding - as though nothing had happened. The recording opens with calls from a Robin at 0:02 and 0:04; then the Robin broadcasts a series of ticking notes at 0:07 until the end of the ninth second. At 0:15 a Blackbird alarms but, just before that, the first wave of House Sparrows erupt into flight at 0:12.  By 0:15 the remainder explode. By the sixteenth second, a total of 80 House Sparrows have left the ground. Those that did not fly away completely (but are still within the bush) start to 'dust themselves down' and are calling. House Sparrows use a 'meep' call when they are agitated. Often it is doubled into a fast repeat that reminds me of the 'meep meep' of the Roadrunner cartoon. Especially from 0:18 onward, a chorus of meep notes can be heard.  Although they are not 'doubled up' on this clip, under other circumstances when just one individual becomes uneasy, it frequently cries wolf with a 'meep meep' that serves as a red alert to all that hear it. In fact, not just House Sparrows react to the signal - but  other birds too.
